description:
Let’s remember the good old days back when tech wasn’t trying to outsmart us

Boring games are making millions: https://youtu.be/PUV5Wjmh_CM

Thanks for watching! :)

comments.text:
Forget the Nintendo Gameboy. When I was a tween in 1991, I got my first Sega Game Gear with Columns for $150 and it lasted for 7 years until my little cousin dropped it from my parents dining room table. Its really a portable Sega Master System.

I saved up my Christmas money that my parents, and aunts had given me, communion, graduation from elementary school. I learned to save for something that I would enjoy as a kid. all the kids that had gameboy wanted to play the GG. My dad got me the TV Tuner as well for GG.

the GG was ahead of its time, but took 6 aa batteries. i also had a puzzle game called junction on GG.

comments.text: Kids nowadays have been taught they will own nothing and enjoy it since it can always be at their fingertips. Easy way to tell if they have common sense or can be offline without issues turn off the internet and have a cell jammer inside of a building. See how long it takes for the ones that need too get off of the most addicting things in the world being the cellphone & tablets. But this also comes from parenting, don't give babies or small children tablets or phones when they are upset or to occupy them. Give them physical tangible toys that make them think and preoccupied that stimulates their brains. It's the early part of nurturing common sense which is hopefully fully developed as you hit early adulthood. Younger generations most of the time never had to troubleshoot their tech if issues arise or opening a computer to fix an issue. Most of this was crap I need to figure this out before mom & dad find out and they might say I broke it when it was just a hiccup in tech. I used to explore whatever operating system I had on a computer so I knew everything on it, same at family member's computers with their permission. Heck there used to be computer lab where you learned how to use a computer, parts of a computer, simple diagnosing issues, how to install and uninstall a program in multiple ways, what to do and watch out for when connecting to the net. No hate on younger generations but companies and legislation taking away the ability and learning to tinker or troubleshoot leading to fixing tech or vehicles has made many things that should not be disposable disposable.

comments.text:
I'm personally trying to slow down with my Internet usage a bit.

I replaced my LCD with a CRT that has a built in DVD player. It's like a bigger version of the CRT I grew up with during the early 2000's. It's even the same brand. I bought some adaptors to hook up my PS4, Xbox One, Wii-U, and Switch (my Wii can just plug in). I have ZERO intention to buy whatever the new Xbox is, a PS5, or a Switch 2. I don't like how the video game market currently is or where it appears to be going. I plan on buying an antenna to get free T.V channels.
I bought an old MacBook Pro and have decided that I would limit my online shopping to that rather than use my phone. That way if I wanna buy something from Amazon, I actually have to wait until I get home to buy it, slowing me down and actually giving me time to think about and research (I still got YouTube on my phone) the product rather than me committing an impulse buy.

Edit: I almost forgot, I have a Victrola 8-In-1 so I can play cassette tapes, vinyl records, CD disks, and listen to radio. For mobile music, I have an iPod.

Went online to buy some new (old) games and discovered that the prices are now bonkers.
